      <abstract displayLabel="Abstract">The set of software metrics introduced by Maurice H. Halstead in the
                1970's has seen much scrutiny and not infrequent criticism. This article takes a
                fresh look at these metrics using quantity calculus (the algebra of units) and a new
                approach to dimensionless units. In this way, it is possible to assign units to the
                major Halstead metrics in a manner that is logically consistent. However, Halstead's
                repurposing of counts of software attributes as counts of unobservable mental events
                leads to a less plausible, more confusing set of metrics for coding effort than for
                software attributes.</abstract>
